{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_1","type":"agent_message","text":"**Topology Summary**\nUse a one-op-amp differential amplifier/subtractor with four matched resistors. The circuit implements `Vout = Vin2 - Vin1` by applying `Vin1` to the inverting side and `Vin2` to the non-inverting side with unity matched ratios.\n\n**Device/Function List**\n- One ideal op amp or high-gain primitive VCVS-style op amp.\n- `R1 = 10 kOhm`: from `Vin1` to the inverting summing node.\n- `R2 = 10 kOhm`: from `Vout` back to the inverting summing node.\n- `R3 = 10 kOhm`: from `Vin2` to the non-inverting reference node.\n- `R4 = 10 kOhm`: from the non-inverting reference node to ground.\n- Independent DC voltage source driving `Vin1`.\n- Independent DC voltage source driving `Vin2`.\n- Independent 5 V supply source defining `VDD`.\n\n**Bias/Reference Strategy**\nUse ground as the 0 V reference and `VDD = 5 V`. For `.op`, choose inputs that keep the ideal subtractor output inside the single-supply range. Recommended test bias: `Vin1 = 1 V`, `Vin2 = 3 V`, expecting `Vout = 2 V`.\n\nIf the op amp primitive includes supply pins, power it from `VDD` and ground. If implemented as a high-gain VCVS, its output should drive `Vout` referenced to ground.\n\n**Signal Or Feedback Path**\n`Vin1` feeds the inverting summing node through `R1`. Negative feedback through `R2` forces the inverting node to match the non-inverting reference node.\n\n`Vin2` feeds the non-inverting node through `R3`, while `R4` to ground creates the matched reference divider. With `R1 = R2 = R3 = R4`, the common-mode terms cancel and the closed-loop output is `Vout = Vin2 - Vin1`.\n\n**SPICE/Netlist Constraints**\n- Final file must be named `p27.cir`.\n- Preserve node names exactly: `Vin1`, `Vin2`, `Vout`.\n- Include `.op`.\n- Explicitly drive both `Vin1` and `Vin2` with independent voltage sources.\n- Use primitive devices only: resistors, voltage sources, and an ideal op amp realized by a primitive high-gain source or equivalent.\n- Do not use subcircuits, hidden models, or behavioral shortcuts unless absolutely unavoidable.\n\n**Failure Risks To Avoid**\n- Do not swap `Vin1` and `Vin2`, or the sign becomes `Vin1 - Vin2`.\n- Do not mismatch resistor ratios; unity subtraction requires `R1 = R2 = R3 = R4`.\n- Do not leave `Vin1`, `Vin2`, or either op amp input node floating.\n- Do not omit a ground reference for the non-inverting network.\n- Do not choose `.op` input values that force `Vout` below ground or above `VDD` in a single-supply setup.\n- Do not accidentally name ports `vin1`, `VIN1`, `out`, or similar; exact names are required."}}
